## Branching and commits

- Work off **`main`**. Feature branches: `<type>/<short-name>` — e.g. `feat/markdown-frontmatter`, `fix/exif-orientation`.
- Commit messages follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/): `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `refactor:`. The first line is a short summary; the body (optional) explains why, not what.
- Sign-off (`git commit -s`) is appreciated but not required.

## Pull requests

1. Open a draft PR early if you'd like feedback on direction.
2. Make sure tests pass locally before marking ready for review.
3. CI must be green: build, tests, lint.
4. PRs are squash-merged unless the change history is genuinely worth preserving.
5. One reviewer minimum; two for changes touching public APIs / security / release pipeline.

PRs should:

- Include tests for new behaviour.
- Update docs if user-facing behaviour changed.
- Update CHANGELOG.md under `[Unreleased]` if applicable.

## Code style

```sh
<format-command>    # e.g. `go fmt ./...`, `prettier --write .`, `cargo fmt`
